   <titles>
      <title>Continuous Functions</title>
      <plain.title>Continuous Functions</plain.title>
   </titles>
   <intro>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we introduce the ‘epsilon-delta’ definition of continuity. It goes back to Bernard Bolzano in 1817. We establish the continuity of certain key functions, namely constant functions, inclusion functions, and the inverse function <math>
                     <latex>p(x)=1/x</latex>
                  </math>. In subsequent sections these form the inputs into operations which generate new continuous functions from given ones.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Then we show that continuity may alternately be characterized by the limit condition <math>
                     <latex>\lim_{n\to \infty}f(t_n)=f(x)</latex>
                  </math> whenever <math>
                     <latex>\lim_{n\to\infty} t_n = x</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </intro>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <def type="Definition" id="Def_EpsilonDeltaContinuity">
               <caption>Epsilon-delta approach to continuity</caption>
               <associate type="Explanation">
                  <unit.ref unitId="Expla_EpsilonDeltaContinuous"/>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>A detailed explanation of what this <math>
                              <latex>\varepsilon</latex>
                           </math>-<math>
                              <latex>\delta</latex>
                           </math> definition means.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <associate type="Explanation">
                  <unit.ref unitId="Expla_EpsilonDeltaDisContinuous"/>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Explanation</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Here we explain how the <math>
                              <latex>\varepsilon</latex>
                           </math>-<math>
                              <latex>\delta</latex>
                           </math> definition of continuity detects and rejects functions which make one or several jumps.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </associate>
               <def.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>A function <math>
                           <latex>f\from D\to \RNr</latex>
                        </math>, <math>
                           <latex>D\subseteq \RNr</latex>
                        </math>, is continuous at <math>
                           <latex>x\in D</latex>
                        </math> if, for every <math>
                           <latex> \varepsilon &gt; 0 </latex>
                        </math>, there exists <math>
                           <latex> \delta &gt; 0 </latex>
                        </math>, such that for all <math>
                           <latex>t\in D</latex>
                        </math>,
				</para.body>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>continuous</term>
                        <term>at a point</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Here continuity at a point is defined via the (<math>
                                    <latex>\varepsilon</latex>
                                 </math>-<math>
                                    <latex>\delta</latex>
                                 </math>)-condition</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>function</term>
                        <term>continuous at a point</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Here continuity of a function at a point is defined via the (<math>
                                    <latex>\varepsilon</latex>
                                 </math>-<math>
                                    <latex>\delta</latex>
                                 </math>)-condition</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex> \Abs{ x-t } &lt; \delta\quad \implies\quad \Abs{ f(x) - f(t) } &lt; \varepsilon </latex>
                  </math.display>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The function is continuous (everywhere) if it is continuous at each <math>
                           <latex>x</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>D</latex>
                        </math>.
				</para.body>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>continuous</term>
                        <term>everywhere</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Here continuity of a function on its entire domain is defined via the (<math>
                                    <latex>\varepsilon</latex>
                                 </math>-<math>
                                    <latex>\delta</latex>
                                 </math>)-condition</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                     <index.glossary>
                        <term>function</term>
                        <term>continuous</term>
                        <info>
                           <para>
                              <para.body>Here continuity of a function on its entire domain is defined via the (<math>
                                    <latex>\varepsilon</latex>
                                 </math>-<math>
                                    <latex>\delta</latex>
                                 </math>)-condition</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
               </def.body>
            </def>
